potentially habitable planets orbit one of these cool stars. 
Aims: Our M-dwarf radial velocity monitoring with HARPS on the ESO 3.6 m
telescope at La Silla observatory makes a major contribution to this
sample. Methods: We present here dense radial velocity (RV) time
series for three M dwarfs observed over \textasciitilde{}five years: GJ 3293 (0.42
M$\odot$), GJ 3341 (0.47 M$\odot$), and GJ 3543 (0.45
M$\odot$). We extracted these RVs through minimum
$\chi$2-matching of each spectrum against a stack of all
observed spectra for the same star that has a high signal-to-noise
ratio. We then compared potential orbital signals against several
stellar activity indicators to distinguish the Keplerian variations
induced by planets from the spurious signals that result from rotational
modulation of stellar surface inhomogeneities and from activity cycles.
 Results: Two Neptune-mass planets - msin(i) = 1.4 $\pm$ 0.1
and 1.3 $\pm$ 0.1Mnept - orbit GJ 3293 with periods P =
