  url = {http://adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2008ApJ...673.1160A},
  doi = {10/dqtvhc},
  shorttitle = {Ocean {{Planet}} or {{Thick Atmosphere}}},
  abstract = {The bulk composition of an exoplanet is commonly inferred from its 
average density. For small planets, however, the average density is not
unique within the range of compositions. Variations of a number of
important planetary parameters\textemdash{}which are difficult or impossible
to constrain from measurements alone\textemdash{}produce planets with the same
average densities but widely varying bulk compositions. We find that
adding a gas envelope equivalent to 0.1\%-10\% of the mass of a solid
planet causes the radius to increase 5\%-60\% above its gas-free value. A
planet with a given mass and radius might have substantial water ice
content (a so-called ocean planet), or alternatively a large rocky iron
core and some H and/or He. For example, a wide variety of compositions
can explain the observed radius of GJ 436b, although all models require
some H/He. We conclude that the identification of water worlds based on
the mass-radius relationship alone is impossible unless a significant
gas layer can be ruled out by other means.},
